        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "[perf] improve reply send performance",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Duplicate of #85853, rebased onto current `openclaw/openclaw:main` at `0ba6b235349add2d1d47b6543b980ee90d93a0df`.\n- Keeps both commits from the original stack:\n  - `fix: avoid blocking reply sends on bookkeeping`\n  - `fix telegram progress tool result preview`\n- Improves reply latency by avoiding dispatcher-idle waits on every direct block reply callback.\n- Flushes pending block delivery only before subsequent tool/progress events, preserving block-before-tool ordering without making lightweight replies wait on dispatcher bookkeeping.\n- Schedules source reply transcript mirroring after successful `message.action` sends without blocking the gateway response, while serializing async mirrors per session to preserve transcript chronology.\n- Sends Telegram direct-message typing earlier after access checks so delayed context/session construction does not postpone the visible typing cue.\n\n## Regression Source\n\n#83722 is the merged regression source. It correctly fixed same-channel pre-tool block ordering by waiting for block reply delivery before tool execution could continue, but the merged implementation placed that delivery barrier directly on the hot block-reply callback path.\n\nThat means lightweight/direct replies can wait for dispatcher idle or delivery bookkeeping even when no later tool/progress event is about to be emitted. Under concurrent embedded runs, cron work, slow channel I/O, or transcript mirroring pressure, the ordering fix from #83722 turns into amplified user-visible reply latency.\n\nThis PR keeps the ordering guarantee introduced by #83722, but moves the wait to the point where ordering matters: before a later tool/progress emission is sent. Direct block replies can resolve without waiting on dispatcher idle, while a subsequent event still flushes pending block delivery first.\n\n## Impact\n\nSimple visible replies can return sooner without compromising user-visible send order. ACP direct block replies remain non-blocking for the common path, block-before-tool/progress chronology is preserved, transcript mirroring stays best-effort after successful source sends, and Telegram direct typing begins earlier without adding a duplicate immediate cue.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\nBehavior addressed: direct visible replies should not be delayed by dispatcher idle waits, source transcript mirroring, or late Telegram typing setup while preserving block-before-tool/progress ordering.\n\nReal environment tested: local OpenClaw source checkout on this rebased branch, with `origin/main` fetched to `0ba6b235349add2d1d47b6543b980ee90d93a0df` before PR creation.\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch: `git diff --check`; `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/auto-reply/reply/dispatch-from-config.test.ts src/auto-reply/reply/dispatch-acp-delivery.test.ts src/gateway/server-methods/send.test.ts extensions/telegram/src/bot-message-context.typing.test.ts extensions/telegram/src/bot-message.test.ts extensions/telegram/src/bot-message-dispatch.test.ts`.\n\nEvidence after fix: branch contains exactly the two duplicated commits on top of current `origin/main`; `git diff --check` was clean; focused Vitest passed 7 files / 381 tests.\n\nObserved result after fix: reply dispatch, ACP delivery, gateway send transcript mirroring, Telegram typing, bot message, and Telegram dispatch regression coverage all passed on the rebased stack.\n\nWhat was not tested: live Telegram/WhatsApp/Discord account roundtrip with real external credentials.\n\n## Verification\n\n- `git diff --check`\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/auto-reply/reply/dispatch-from-config.test.ts src/auto-reply/reply/dispatch-acp-delivery.test.ts src/gateway/server-methods/send.test.ts extensions/telegram/src/bot-message-context.typing.test.ts extensions/telegram/src/bot-message.test.ts extensions/telegram/src/bot-message-dispatch.test.ts`\n",
